com.whirvis.jraknet

Class RakNetPacket

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.whirvis.jraknet.Packet
      • com.whirvis.jraknet.RakNetPacket
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    AcknowledgedPacket, ChatPacket, ConnectedPing, ConnectedPong, ConnectionBanned, ConnectionRequest, ConnectionRequestAccepted, CustomPacket, IncompatibleProtocolVersion, NewIncomingConnection, OpenConnectionRequestOne, OpenConnectionRequestTwo, OpenConnectionResponseOne, OpenConnectionResponseTwo, UnconnectedPing, UnconnectedPong

    public class RakNetPacket
extends Packet
    A generic RakNet packet that has the ability to get the ID of the packet along with encoding and decoding.
    Since:
    JRakNet v1.0.0
    Author:
    Trent Summerlin

      • ID_SND_RECEIPT_ACKED

        public static final short ID_SND_RECEIPT_ACKED
        The ID of the SND_RECEIPT_ACKED packet.

        In the original implementation of RakNet, when a packet is acknowledged by a peer this packet is sent back through loopback to the original sender of the packet with the acknoweldgeable reliability. Since this implementation has listeners will special built in acknowledgement and loss methods, this packet has no need for implementation.

        public static final short ID_SND_RECEIPT_LOSS
        The ID of the SND_RECEIPT_LOSS packet.

        In the original implementation of RakNet, when a packet is acknowledged by a peer this packet is sent back through loopback to the original sender of the packet with the acknoweldgeable reliability. Since this implementation has listeners will special built in acknowledgement and loss methods, this packet has no need for implementation.

      • ID_USER_PACKET_ENUM

        public static final short ID_USER_PACKET_ENUM
        This is the first ID that the user can for the IDs of their packets. Since packet IDs are written using Packet.writeUnsignedByte(int), the highest packet ID that can be used is 0xFF.

        If one must have more than 121 packet IDs (0xFF - ID_USER_PACKET_ENUM), then one can have a singular ID that they use for all of their user packets with another field to be the packet ID.

        See Also:

        private static void mapNameIds()
        Maps all public packet IDs to their respective field names and vice-versa.

        Packet IDs ID_CUSTOM_0, ID_CUSTOM_1, ID_CUSTOM_2, ID_CUSTOM_3, ID_CUSTOM_4, ID_CUSTOM_5, ID_CUSTOM_6, ID_CUSTOM_7, ID_CUSTOM_8, ID_CUSTOM_9, ID_CUSTOM_A, ID_CUSTOM_B, ID_CUSTOM_C, ID_CUSTOM_D, ID_CUSTOM_E, ID_CUSTOM_F, ID_ACK, and ID_NACK will never are ignored as they are not only internal packets but they also override other packets with the same ID.

      • readConnectionType

        public final ConnectionType readConnectionType()
                                        throws RakNetException
        Reads a ConnectionType.

        This method will check to make sure if there is at least enough data to read the the connection type magic before reading the data. This is due to the fact that this is meant to be used strictly at the end of packets that can be used to signify the protocol implementation of the sender.

        Returns:
        a ConnectionType, ConnectionType.VANILLA if not enough data to read one is present.
        Throws:
        RakNetException - if not enough data is present in the packet after the connection type magic or there are duplicate keys in the metadata.
